"Yes, sir. They should be on their way now; we gave them time to pack food from the cafeteria." At 05:00, the Exodus platoon assembled at the vehicle yard. Captain Xiao stood on a crate and began to speak.
"We will be heading to the I-131 forward operating base located 50 miles outside of Ianelos City. We will support the ongoing siege operation and then attack Ianelos City to clear out the insurgents there. We will use this as a base to advance into the mountains," Captain Xiao explained. "Take your squad and get ready to move out."
The platoon spread out, and each squad climbed into a tank under the leadership of their squad leader. Kollen climbed onto a tank at the front of the convoy and sat with Nimitz, Kress, and two new recruits. Kollen remembered they had arrived just a few days ago, but he didn't know them well. He sat on the edge of the tank with his legs dangling, adjusting his backpack and radio equipment and connecting it to his headset and throat microphone.
"Hey, Kollen, is Harris still keeping Snowball?" Nimitz asked after they had settled in.
"Are you saying he stole that chicken?" Kollen recalled the scene from that morning when they had stolen the chicken from the farm. "Exactly, I'm sure of it."
Kollen looked toward another tank and saw Harris and his squad. He caught a glimpse of a small chicken peering around from behind Harris's backpack.
"Exactly, he's still keeping that chicken," Kollen replied as the tank's turret hatch slammed open and the tank commander appeared in front of them.
"All tanks are moving out," the tank commander said calmly and clearly into his headset. The armored company's tanks and Schick armored cars roared to life and began advancing. Kollen's Cronostan tank released its brakes and moved forward, joining the formation. The tanks formed a wedge formation as they crossed the Itanian plain. The winter blizzard had frozen the wetlands and forests, but the mud remained.
After about an hour, a new recruit (whose name Kollen remembered was Olsen) spoke up and asked, "Lieutenant, have you been on the front lines since the war began?"
"Exactly, I've been here since the Firestorm Operation," Kollen replied. "We thought the fighting would end within a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimated? That's an understatement," Nimitz joined the conversation. "Their weapons and numbers exceeded our expectations. They shot down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Dammit, we should have been able to see it on the road."
"Alright, I will bravely fight for the Federation," Olsen said firmly, "I won't be intimidated by those terrorists."
"Right now you're saying that, but from what I've seen, most new recruits your age run for cover the moment they hear gunfire," Kress said.
"We'll see about that," Kollen said with a smile. Olsen said nothing else.
"Exodus Second-in-Command! Exodus Commander!" Kollen's radio crackled. "We have a heat signature 350 yards at 20 degrees to our right front."
Kollen climbed onto the tank and put on his optical goggles. After switching to thermal imaging mode, he spotted the heat signature in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," Kollen said into his throat mic.
"Are they enemies?" another new recruit, Natalia, asked.
"Can't make them out," Kollen said, switching on his mic. "Exodus platoon, don't open fire unless attacked, first get them out."
As they drew closer, the faint heat signatures transformed from blurred spots into clearer outlines. One of them ran toward somewhere, picked up something, and then ran back to the small ridge. Next, these people crouched down and took up firing positions.
"We've encountered the enemy!" Captain Xiao shouted over the radio as orange tracers shot from the ridge. Bullets pinged off the side of the tank, and the assault troops jumped off the tanks and took cover behind them. A anti-tank missile screamed in and slammed into the ground behind the tank column, shrapnel hitting one of the tanks. Another missile struck the side of a Schick armored personnel carrier (APS-Cerberus) and exploded. After the ammunition detonated, the crew members inside the APC scrambled out, seeking cover.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees to your right, 300 yards. Fire!" the tank platoon leader shouted over the radio. The main guns of Iron 1-2 and 1-3 fired, shells screaming toward the ridge, sending dirt and debris flying into the air from the explosions.
"Deploy the sentry bots!" Knox shouted, who was observing the ridge with a telescope. The rear hatch of a "Hellhound" opened, and a soldier without a weapon stepped out, wearing a custom headset. He barked orders into a square microphone, and two "Sentry" robots responded, their slender metal arms and legs swinging forward as they sprinted quickly. The robots were equipped with weapons, but all were slung over their backs.
"Kill or capture?" Kress asked as he observed.
"It looks like they want to capture alive," Kollen guessed, watching as the two sentry robots disappeared into the ash and smoke. Shouts and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but soon faded. After a while, the two sentry robots returned, dragging a person with them, leaving a trail of boot prints on the ground. Upon reaching the safe zone, the robots threw the captive to the ground, where he landed heavily in the mud and snow, groaning in pain.
He struggled to get up as Captain Xiao approached. Captain Xiao turned to one of the sentries. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," the sentry robot replied. "The rest have fled on foot."
Captain Xiao nodded, turned to Kollen and Kress who were standing nearby, and said, "Can the two of you take this person away?"
